'''Smoking in East Timor''' is highly common, with the country having a high percentage of smokers.<ref name="The country where nearly two-thirds of men smoke">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-27677882|title=The country where nearly two-thirds of men smoke|publisher=BBC News|first=Peter |last=Taylor|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> An estimate 33% of the population smoke daily, with 61% of East Timorese men who use tobacco products regularly.<ref name="The country where nearly two-thirds of men smoke"/> Although it is required that packaging display warnings, this is rendered largely ineffective by the large amount of East Timorese adults who cannot read. There is very little restriction on Tobacco advertisement and it is common to see teachers and students smoking in school.<ref name="The country where nearly two-thirds of men smoke"/>

A study in 2008 found that stress brought on from poverty and [[Indonesian occupation of East Timor|the struggle for independence]] significantly contributed towards youth smoking.<ref>Fanda, Robert & Brown, David. W., (2008) [http://medind.nic.in/ibv/t08/i12/ibvt08i12p961.pdf "Smoking among Youth in East Timor-Leste: What are the Dynamics?"]. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Volume 45, December 17, 2008</ref> Former President and independence activists [[Xanana Gusmão]] is himself a heavy smoker who said that cigarettes helped him and his colleges stay calm while they were fighting the Indonesians.<ref name="The country where nearly two-thirds of men smoke"/> As with neighboring Indonesia tobacco advertisement is prevalent and cigarettes are cheap, only around 25 cents per pack.<ref name="The country where nearly two-thirds of men smoke"/>

In November 2015 the East Timorese government promised tighter rules governing tobacco consumption.<ref>{{cite web|title=East Timor tackles cigarette smoking with a new law to control tobacco|url=http://www.easttimorlawandjusticebulletin.com/2015/11/east-timor-tackles-cigarette-smoking.html|work=East Timor Law and Justice Bulletin|date=27 November 2015|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>

